        1,
        "**Quadratic Equations**\n\n"
        "Quadratic equations are among the most heavily tested topics in SAT Advanced Math. A **quadratic equation** is any equation that can be written in **standard form**: ax² + bx + c = 0, where a ≠ 0. The graph of a quadratic is a U-shaped curve called a **parabola**. Understanding how to solve quadratic equations efficiently is essential for earning a top SAT Math score.\n\n"
        "**Method 1 — Factoring**\n\n"
        "Factoring is the fastest method when it works. The goal is to rewrite ax² + bx + c as a product of two binomials. For equations where a = 1, find two numbers p and q such that p × q = c and p + q = b. Then factor as (x + p)(x + q) = 0 and apply the **Zero Product Property**: if a product equals zero, at least one factor must equal zero. Set each factor to zero and solve.\n\n"
        "Example: Solve x² − 5x + 6 = 0. Find two numbers that multiply to 6 and add to −5: those are −2 and −3. Factor: (x − 2)(x − 3) = 0. Solutions: x = 2 or x = 3.\n\n"
        "**Method 2 — Quadratic Formula**\n\n"
        "When factoring is not obvious, use the **quadratic formula**:\n\n"
        "x = (−b ± √(b² − 4ac)) / (2a)\n\n"
        "This formula is derived by completing the square on the general form ax² + bx + c = 0. Divide through by a, move c/a to the right, add (b/2a)² to both sides to complete the square, and simplify — the quadratic formula falls out naturally. Always identify a, b, and c carefully before substituting.\n\n"
        "**Method 3 — Completing the Square**\n\n"
        "**Completing the square** converts the equation into the form (x + d)² = e, which you solve by taking square roots. Steps: (1) Move c to the right side. (2) Divide every term by a if a ≠ 1. (3) Add (b/2)² to both sides. (4) Write the left side as a perfect square. (5) Take the square root of both sides (include ±). (6) Solve for x.\n\n"
        "Example: Solve x² + 6x − 7 = 0. Move −7: x² + 6x = 7. Add (3)² = 9: x² + 6x + 9 = 16. Factor: (x + 3)² = 16. Take square roots: x + 3 = ±4. So x = 1 or x = −7.\n\n"
        "**The Discriminant**\n\n"
        "The expression under the radical in the quadratic formula, b² − 4ac, is called the **discriminant** and tells you how many real solutions exist without fully solving the equation:\n\n"
        "- b² − 4ac > 0 → two distinct real roots (the parabola crosses the x-axis twice)\n"
        "- b² − 4ac = 0 → exactly one repeated real root (the parabola touches the x-axis at the vertex)\n"
        "- b² − 4ac < 0 → no real roots (the parabola does not cross the x-axis)\n\n"
        "**SAT-Style Worked Examples**\n\n"
        "Example 1: Solve 2x² + 3x − 2 = 0 by factoring. Multiply a × c = 2 × (−2) = −4. Find two numbers that multiply to −4 and add to 3: they are 4 and −1. Rewrite: 2x² + 4x − x − 2 = 0. Factor by grouping: 2x(x + 2) − 1(x + 2) = 0, giving (2x − 1)(x + 2) = 0. Solutions: x = 1/2 or x = −2.\n\n"
        "Example 2: How many real solutions does 3x² − 6x + 3 = 0 have? Compute the discriminant: (−6)² − 4(3)(3) = 36 − 36 = 0. Exactly one real (repeated) solution: x = 1.\n\n"
        "Example 3: A ball’s height (in feet) is given by h(t) = −4t² + 8t + 5. At what times is the ball at ground level (h = 0)? Solve −4t² + 8t + 5 = 0, or 4t² − 8t − 5 = 0. Discriminant: 64 + 80 = 144. t = (8 ± 12) / 8. So t = 2.5 or t = −0.5. Reject the negative time; the ball hits the ground at t = 2.5 seconds.\n\n"
        "**Common Traps**\n\n"
        "- Forgetting the ± in the quadratic formula — always write both roots.\n"
        "- Sign errors when factoring: (x − 3)(x + 2) = 0 gives x = 3 and x = −2, not the opposite.\n"
        "- Dividing by x early (e.g., x² = 3x becomes x = 3 only — you lose the x = 0 solution).\n\n"
        "**SAT Tip:** On the Digital SAT, factoring is usually the fastest method when the roots are integers or simple fractions. If you cannot spot the factors within 20 seconds, switch directly to the quadratic formula. Never waste time forcing factoring on a messy problem."
