        2,
        "**Quadratic Functions and Parabolas**\n\n"
        "A **quadratic function** is a function of the form f(x) = ax² + bx + c. Its graph is a **parabola** — a symmetric, U-shaped curve. Understanding the structure of a parabola lets you answer SAT questions about maximum values, zeros, and real-world models without plugging in many numbers.\n\n"
        "**Vertex Form**\n\n"
        "The most informative way to write a quadratic function is **vertex form**: f(x) = a(x − h)² + k. The **vertex** is the point (h, k), and it represents the minimum of the parabola when a > 0 (opens upward) or the maximum when a < 0 (opens downward). The **axis of symmetry** is the vertical line x = h, which divides the parabola into two mirror-image halves.\n\n"
        "[[figure:parabola|A parabola with vertex, axis of symmetry, and zeros labeled]]\n\n"
        "**Converting Standard Form to Vertex Form**\n\n"
        "Complete the square on f(x) = ax² + bx + c. Factor out a from the first two terms: a(x² + (b/a)x) + c. Add and subtract (b/2a)² inside the parentheses: a[(x + b/2a)² − (b/2a)²] + c. Simplify to get a(x + b/2a)² + (c − b²/4a). So h = −b/(2a) and k = f(h).\n\n"
        "**Finding Zeros from Factored Form**\n\n"
        "When f(x) = a(x − r)(x − s), the zeros (x-intercepts) are x = r and x = s. The **Vieta’s formulas** give a shortcut: for ax² + bx + c = 0, the **sum of the roots** equals −b/a and the **product of the roots** equals c/a. These are extremely useful on the SAT when a problem asks for the sum or product of solutions without requiring you to solve the full equation.\n\n"
        "Example: For 2x² − 10x + 8 = 0, the sum of roots = −(−10)/2 = 5 and the product of roots = 8/2 = 4. Roots are 1 and 4 (check: 1 + 4 = 5, 1 × 4 = 4).\n\n"
        "**Interpreting a, h, and k in Context**\n\n"
        "SAT word problems often present a quadratic like h(t) = −4.9(t − 3)² + 44.1, where h is height in meters and t is time in seconds. Here:\n\n"
        "- a = −4.9 tells you the object is falling (opens downward)\n"
        "- h = 3 means the maximum height occurs at t = 3 seconds\n"
        "- k = 44.1 is the maximum height (44.1 meters)\n\n"
        "Always read the context carefully to match the vertex coordinates to real-world meaning.\n\n"
        "**SAT-Style Worked Examples**\n\n"
        "Example 1: The function f(x) = −2(x − 4)² + 18 has its maximum at what point? The vertex is (4, 18) and since a = −2 < 0, this is a maximum. Maximum value is 18.\n\n"
        "Example 2: A parabola has zeros at x = −1 and x = 5. What is its axis of symmetry? The axis of symmetry is the average of the zeros: x = (−1 + 5)/2 = 2.\n\n"
        "Example 3: For f(x) = x² − 6x + 5, find the vertex and state whether it is a minimum or maximum. Convert: x² − 6x + 9 − 9 + 5 = (x − 3)² − 4. Vertex is (3, −4); since a = 1 > 0, this is a minimum.\n\n"
        "**Common Traps**\n\n"
        "- Misreading vertex form: f(x) = (x − 3)² has vertex at x = +3, not x = −3.\n"
        "- Confusing the axis of symmetry formula: it is x = −b/(2a), not x = b/(2a).\n"
        "- Assuming the largest y-value in a table is always the vertex — only true if the table hits the exact vertex.\n\n"
        "**SAT Tip:** When an SAT problem gives a quadratic in vertex form and asks for the maximum or minimum value, the answer is simply k. You do not need to graph or plug in values. This saves 30–60 seconds per question."
